<p>Page III (at the beginning), from the first indent.</p>
<p>I could never have come to know the habits of ants if I had not undertaken to study them since my childhood, guided by the work of Pierre Huber.<ref target="#foot.f5"/> Later so much time is no longer at one’s disposal, which is my greatest regret, for one could employ many more human lifetimes on the study of ant habits alone.</p>
<p>Need I add, Sir, that the light your work has shed on all the natural sciences shines also on the little world of ants, and allows a host of facts to be perceived there that would in its absence have been totally incomprehensible (e.g. the series concerning the slave-making instinct, indicated at the top of p. 443).<ref target="#foot.f6"/> I hope I have not presumed too much of my work in thinking that it might interest you; I remain, Sir, yours very truly, | D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Aug. Forel | Junior doctor at the | Distric Lunatic Asylum, | Munich | Bavaria</p> 
